    {
        "content": "<p>Still no <span aria-label=\"frown\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f641\" role=\"img\" title=\"frown\">:frown:</span></p>",
        "id": 219679490,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1607733813
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't really have an answer, but I'm working on a very similar issue (with tensor products rather than product measures) here: <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/issues/5311\">#5311</a>. Right now I'm just basically duplicating the binary tensor product code but a trick like this would be nice. It's not clear how much one gets for free this way though, it seems like most of the API still has to get written anyway, and copy/pasting proofs can be a lot faster to write even if it's more lines of code in the end.</p>",
        "id": 219679668,
        "sender_full_name": "Frédéric Dupuis",
        "timestamp": 1607733967
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"311453\">Frédéric Dupuis</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/From.20binary.20products.20to.20finitary.20products/near/219679668\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Right now I'm just basically duplicating the binary tensor product code but a trick like this would be nice. It's not clear how much one gets for free this way though, it seems like most of the API still has to get written anyway, and copy/pasting proofs can be a lot faster to write even if it's more lines of code in the end.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Would it be easier to get a \"trick\" going the other way, from a general finitary version to a binary version?</p>",
        "id": 219679732,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1607734059
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But the category theory limits are not explicit, so it might not be useful in this context anyway...</p>",
        "id": 219679782,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1607734083
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sounds much easier that way, going from <code>Π i : (fin 2), β i</code> to the binary version should be pretty simple.</p>",
        "id": 219679851,
        "sender_full_name": "Frédéric Dupuis",
        "timestamp": 1607734177
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"260507\">Heather Macbeth</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/From.20binary.20products.20to.20finitary.20products/near/219679149\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A naive question -- is there any way to get the finitary product measure \"all at once\" rather than by iterating the binary one?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't know, but I have looked at a couple of books, and they all just say \"iterate the binary product\".<br>\nIt would be pretty tricky, since the binary product of measures is defined as a unary integral. The <code>n</code>-ary product would be something like an <code>n-1</code>-ary integral, which sounds pretty hairy.</p>",
        "id": 219679934,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1607734238
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The issue with the iterated binary product is that there is an inherent order in which the product is taken, which (at least in the case I'm working on) is not desirable in the final product. And it doesn't seem easy to get rid of.</p>",
        "id": 219680055,
        "sender_full_name": "Frédéric Dupuis",
        "timestamp": 1607734360
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, wait, my previous message was misleading. I <em>define</em> the finitary product measure directly:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"sd\">/-- `measure.pi μ` is the finite product of the measures `{μ i | i : ι}`.</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">  It is defined to be the maximal product measure, i.e.</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">  the maximal measure `ν` with the property that `ν (pi univ s) ≤ ∏ i, μ i (s i)`,</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">  where `pi univ s` is the product of the sets `{ s i | i : ι }`. -/</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">protected</span> <span class=\"kd\">def</span> <span class=\"n\">pi</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">measure</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Π</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">α</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"bp\">...</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>However, now I need to show that <code>ν (pi univ s) = ∏ i, μ i (s i)</code>. To show this, I need to know that there is <em>some</em> measure that has this property. And for this I want to use iterated binary products. So I only use a specific order in which the product is taken to prove some properties, not to define anything.</p>",
        "id": 219680350,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1607734690
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"243562\">Adam Topaz</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/From.20binary.20products.20to.20finitary.20products/near/219679382\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think there is this? <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/category_theory.limits.has_finite_products_of_has_binary_products\">docs#category_theory.limits.has_finite_products_of_has_binary_products</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>there's nothing of this form in mathlib (yet) for categories, i'm planning to pr it fairly soon though</p>",
        "id": 219680470,
        "sender_full_name": "Bhavik Mehta",
        "timestamp": 1607734850
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the definition of <code>list.pmap</code> is relevant to these considerations. Something similar comes up when lifting that to quotients in <code>multiset.pmap</code></p>",
